Yes, that's a missing case. I'm planning to do as below to cover that, as I think this is cleaner than adding a first-polling-check flag, or overriding the start() method of gpio class:


    int ChassisIntrusionGpioSensor::readSensor()
    {
       // mGpioLine.event_read();
       auto value = mGpioLine.get_value();
       return value;
    }

    void ChassisIntrusionGpioSensor::pollSensorStatus()
    {
       mGpioFd.async_wait(...,[]()
         {
             if (ec) return;
             else {
                 mGpioLine.event_read();
                 // trigger next polling
                 pollSensorStatus();
             }
         });

      // This is to cover the initial reading.
      // And on a gpioline event, value will be read and published on the next call 
      // to pollSensorStatus()
      int value = readSensor();
      if (value >= 0)
      {
         updateValue(value);
      }
    }

Once an event happens, it calls to pollSensorStatus to trigger next polling, and the value of that event will be read only after the next polling is registered. This way, the initial value can be trieved on the first call to polling, too. Do you think the above implementation is fine? I believe no event can jump in before pollSensorStatus() completes, so it won't cause Read-after-write hazard, right?
